  <main>
    <section class="hero">
      <div class="container">
        <span class="badge">Digital Marketing & Content Analytics Portfolio</span>
        <h1>Turning messy brand signals into measurable customer journeys.</h1>
        <p class="hero-text">
          I am a communication and media analytics graduate building toward Digital Marketing, Marketing Analyst and E-commerce Marketing roles in Hong Kong. This portfolio demonstrates how I connect public user insight, positioning diagnosis, content strategy, CRM thinking, GA4-style measurement and dashboard reporting.
        </p>
        <div class="actions">
          <a class="button" href="#case">View Featured Case Study</a>
          <a class="button secondary" href="mailto:lirielzhang07@gmail.com">Contact Me</a>
          <a class="button secondary" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/wenli-zhang-693ba2299" target="_blank">LinkedIn</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="case">
      <div class="container">
        <span class="badge dark">Featured Case Study</span>
        <h2>Remote Digital Journey Audit & Growth Proposal for Preface Coffee & Wine</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          <strong>Clarifying the Coffee-and-Learn experience from online discovery to community engagement.</strong>
          This self-initiated case study audits PCW’s publicly visible digital touchpoints and user-generated content, then proposes how its refined tech-infused lifestyle space can turn offline interest into digital interaction, CRM follow-up and repeat engagement.
        </p>

        <div class="grid two">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Project Objective</h3>
            <p>
              To diagnose how PCW’s Coffee-and-Learn concept is understood across public touchpoints and design a clearer customer journey from café discovery to micro-learning, lead capture, event participation and repeat engagement.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Scope</h3>
            <p>
              Remote brand audit, public UGC insight, layered positioning diagnosis, offline-to-digital journey design, content strategy, CRM thinking, GA4-style measurement and dashboard logic.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout">
          <h3>Core Diagnosis</h3>
          <p>
            PCW does not lack brand assets. It already has a refined space, Tech Dose cards, tech-themed cup sleeves, AI-Q and community/event cues. The central challenge is connecting these offline experience cues into a clearer, measurable digital journey.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid three">
          <div class="card soft">
            <h4>Business Problem</h4>
            <p>PCW’s Coffee-and-Learn concept is differentiated, but first-time users may not immediately understand how coffee, tech content, events and community are connected.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card soft">
            <h4>Marketing Goal</h4>
            <p>Move users from a simple café/light-work entry point into Tech Dose interaction, AI-Q engagement, newsletter/event sign-up and repeat visits.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card soft">
            <h4>Data Approach</h4>
            <p>Use public brand materials, Xiaohongshu/Instagram UGC, visible touchpoint analysis, simulated funnel data and GA4-style metrics to demonstrate insight-to-action thinking.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="brand">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>1. Brand & Touchpoint Audit</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          PCW should be understood as a Coffee-and-Learn Hub rather than simply a café or a course-selling channel. It uses coffee and wine as low-pressure lifestyle entry points to introduce bite-sized tech knowledge, experiential learning, events and community engagement.
        </p>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Area</th>
              <th>Diagnosis</th>
              <th>Marketing Implication</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Brand Positioning</td>
              <td>PCW is positioned as a Daily Coffee-and-Learn Hub: a hybrid lifestyle-learning space combining coffee, wine, tech knowledge, events and community.</td>
              <td>Use layered positioning: café/light-work as the simple entry point, Coffee-and-Learn as the differentiation layer.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Core Asset</td>
              <td>The core asset is not a single Tech Dose card or AI-Q Test, but a refined, low-pressure lifestyle space with a tech-infused learning atmosphere.</td>
              <td>Tech Dose, cup sleeves, AI-Q and events should support the broader space experience rather than remain isolated features.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Supporting Systems</td>
              <td>Tech Dose cards, tech-themed cup sleeves, AI-Q, events and partnership campaigns make the Coffee-and-Learn concept visible.</td>
              <td>These systems need to become more interactive, trackable and connected to follow-up actions.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Main Challenge</td>
              <td>Offline interest may not yet be clearly converted into digital interaction, lead capture, CRM follow-up and repeat engagement.</td>
              <td>Build a clearer offline-to-digital journey through QR, AI-Q, newsletter, event sign-up and CRM.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="positioning">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>2. Positioning Diagnosis: Layered Positioning</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          PCW does not need to choose between being a work-friendly café and a tech-learning space. A more practical strategy is layered positioning: use the café, light-work and lifestyle setting as a low-barrier acquisition hook, while using Tech Dose cards, AI-Q, QR-based content and events to guide users toward the broader Coffee-and-Learn experience.
        </p>

        <div class="grid three">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="mini-label">Simple Entry Point</div>
            <h3>Café / Light Work / Lifestyle</h3>
            <p>
              First-time users need an easy way to understand the space. A café/light-work message lowers the entry barrier, but should avoid overpromising a quiet co-working environment.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card tech">
            <div class="mini-label">Differentiation Layer</div>
            <h3>Tech Dose / AI-Q / Coffee-and-Learn</h3>
            <p>
              Once users engage with the space, the brand needs to show that it is not just another café. Tech Dose, AI-Q and in-store learning cues make the difference visible.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card gold">
            <div class="mini-label">Relationship Layer</div>
            <h3>Events / CRM / Repeat Visits</h3>
            <p>
              The deeper opportunity is to convert curiosity into relationship: newsletter sign-up, salon participation, repeat visits and learning-related engagement.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="quote">
          Recommended approach: simple entry, clear bridge, differentiated engagement.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="ugc">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>3. Public UGC Insight</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          Public UGC suggests mixed customer perception. Some users recognise PCW’s tech-infused Coffee-and-Learn experience, while others approach it more simply as a work/study-friendly café. The latter can be a useful acquisition hook, but it also creates expectation risk if quiet seating, space availability, event booking or service flow does not match that use case.
        </p>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>UGC Signal</th>
              <th>What It Suggests</th>
              <th>Marketing Implication</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Positive UGC notices coffee + technology.</td>
              <td>The Coffee-and-Learn concept can be understood when the tech layer is visible through cards, cups and in-store cues.</td>
              <td>Amplify visible tech-learning moments through social content and UGC prompts.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Some users visit as a work/study café.</td>
              <td>Xiaohongshu recommendations may shape expectations around quiet space, seating and work-friendliness.</td>
              <td>Use “light work” carefully as an acquisition hook, while managing expectations around event use and space availability.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Tech Dose cards and cup sleeves are memorable.</td>
              <td>Coffee itself can become a micro-content medium, not just a drink.</td>
              <td>Turn static content cues into QR-based interactions and measurable digital touchpoints.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Negative experience can emerge when expectations mismatch.</td>
              <td>If users expect a quiet co-working environment, event booking, noise or unclear service flow may cause disappointment.</td>
              <td>Clarify use cases: coffee break, light work, Tech Dose, event, salon, not guaranteed quiet study space.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="pain">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>4. Pain Point Diagnosis</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          The main issue is not that PCW lacks experience assets. The issue is that these assets need to be connected into a clearer offline-to-digital journey that captures interest, nurtures users and encourages repeat engagement.
        </p>

        <div class="grid four">
          <div class="card tech">
            <div class="mini-label">Main Pain Point</div>
            <h3>Weak Offline-to-Digital Journey</h3>
            <p>In-store interest may not be converted into measurable digital actions such as QR scans, AI-Q completion, newsletter sign-up or event registration.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="mini-label">Supporting Issue</div>
            <h3>Complex Value Hierarchy</h3>
            <p>PCW combines coffee, wine, tech knowledge, AI-Q, events, courses and venue use, which may make the first-time user journey complex.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="mini-label">Supporting Issue</div>
            <h3>Shallow Tech Touchpoints</h3>
            <p>Tech Dose and cup sleeves create memorability, but may remain passive if not connected to interaction or lead capture.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="mini-label">Supporting Issue</div>
            <h3>Mixed UGC Expectations</h3>
            <p>Users may enter through a work/study café perception, which can create expectation risk if the actual experience differs.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="journey">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>5. Core Strategy Framework: Coffee-and-Learn Journey</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          The core strategy is to turn PCW’s Coffee-and-Learn concept into a staged customer journey. Instead of treating Tech Dose cards, cup sleeves and AI-Q as isolated experience elements, the proposal connects them into a measurable path from discovery to repeat engagement.
        </p>

        <div class="journey">
          <div class="journey-step">
            <div class="journey-number">1</div>
            <h4>Online Discovery</h4>
            <p>Users discover PCW through Instagram, Xiaohongshu, Google or public UGC.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="journey-step">
            <div class="journey-number">2</div>
            <h4>In-store Experience</h4>
            <p>Users experience the refined space, coffee/wine setting and tech-learning atmosphere.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="journey-step">
            <div class="journey-number">3</div>
            <h4>Micro-learning Touchpoint</h4>
            <p>Users notice Tech Dose cards, cup sleeves or Today’s Tech Dose content.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="journey-step">
            <div class="journey-number">4</div>
            <h4>Digital Interaction</h4>
            <p>Users scan QR, take AI-Q, unlock a short insight or complete a playful quiz.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="journey-step">
            <div class="journey-number">5</div>
            <h4>Lead Capture & CRM</h4>
            <p>Users subscribe, leave email/WhatsApp, receive AI-Q results or event reminders.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="journey-step">
            <div class="journey-number">6</div>
            <h4>Community & Repeat</h4>
            <p>Users join salons, revisit the store, attend events or explore deeper learning.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Stage</th>
              <th>User Mindset</th>
              <th>Brand Task</th>
              <th>CTA</th>
              <th>Metric</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Online Discovery</td>
              <td>“What is this place? Is it for me?”</td>
              <td>Use an easy café/light-work entry message without reducing the brand to a normal study café.</td>
              <td>View location / learn more</td>
              <td>impressions, profile visits, website clicks</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>In-store Experience</td>
              <td>“How is this different from a normal café?”</td>
              <td>Make the tech-learning atmosphere visible through screens, QR prompts, cards and event cues.</td>
              <td>Notice Tech Dose / scan QR</td>
              <td>QR exposure, QR scan rate</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Micro-learning Touchpoint</td>
              <td>“This is interesting, but how is it relevant to me?”</td>
              <td>Make Tech Dose more useful, playful and user-relevant.</td>
              <td>Scan today’s insight</td>
              <td>content views, scan-to-view rate</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Digital Interaction</td>
              <td>“I can try this quickly.”</td>
              <td>Provide low-friction interaction such as AI-Q, persona quiz or scan-to-collect content.</td>
              <td>Take AI-Q / unlock result</td>
              <td>AI-Q start rate, completion rate</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Lead Capture & CRM</td>
              <td>“I will leave my contact if I get something useful.”</td>
              <td>Offer value exchange: detailed result, free coffee, weekly Tech Dose or event reminder.</td>
              <td>Subscribe / join event list</td>
              <td>email capture rate, open rate, click rate</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Community & Repeat</td>
              <td>“I may come back or join something next time.”</td>
              <td>Use salons, event recaps, member prompts and recommendations to encourage repeat engagement.</td>
              <td>Join next salon / revisit</td>
              <td>event sign-up, repeat visit, repeat participation</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="strategy">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>6. Experience Upgrade Strategy</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          The strategy should not simply add more “technology-looking” elements. Instead, it should make the tech-learning experience more visible, playful, interactive and connected to follow-up actions.
        </p>

        <div class="grid four">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Clarify Entry Message</h3>
            <p>Use easy but accurate acquisition hooks such as “a tech-inspired café for coffee, light work and ideas,” avoiding overpromises around quiet study.</p>
            <div class="tag-row">
              <span class="tag">Acquisition</span>
              <span class="tag">Positioning</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Upgrade In-store Tech</h3>
            <p>Use Today’s Tech Dose Wall, QR-based table prompts and clear event cues so users can understand the Coffee-and-Learn idea within 30 seconds.</p>
            <div class="tag-row">
              <span class="tag">O2O</span>
              <span class="tag">Experience</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Make Learning Playful</h3>
            <p>Turn Tech Dose into a collectible series and add a Coffee-and-Learn Persona Quiz to make micro-learning more shareable and repeatable.</p>
            <div class="tag-row">
              <span class="tag">Content</span>
              <span class="tag">UGC</span>
            </div>
